The project‚Äôs most high-profile test came three and a half years ago, when the Crew Module Atmospheric Reentry Experiment (#CARE) successfully demonstrated that the spacecraft could withstand the rigors of atmospheric reentry.

Making an effort to extend space research, the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO), has started working on building igloo-like habitats on the lunar surface for potential future missions, according to a report by The Times of India.
The moon is a crucial and close destination for research and planetary exploration not just for ISRO but many of the world‚Äôs national and international space agencies (such as NASA, ESA, and others). Lunar missions are the first steps in expanding the manned and unmanned exploration of our solar system.
The moon can be used as a laboratory with lower gravity (1/6 of the earth‚Äôs gravity field) as it is the closest and most accessible planetary object from Earth.With that in mind, the space research organisation has planned to build ‚Äòlunar habitats,‚Äô which will serve as an ‚Äúoutpost‚Äù by sending robots and 3D printers to the Moon. It will be built by using the soil there, as well as other materials.
M Annadurai, Director, ISRO Satellite Centre (ISAC) told the TOI, ‚ÄúWe are planning to use the Moon as an outpost‚Äîlike missions in Antarctica. In the long run, the space station is likely to be scrapped. Many countries, including the US, are considering building more permanent structures on the Moon and working out of there. When that happens, we want India to have contributed.‚Äù

Five satellites of the Indian Space Research Organisation (Isro) are playing a key role in saving lives in rain-battered Kerala by monitoring the flood situation and assisting the state in disaster management.

‚ÄúWe are using the data from these satellites to provide alerts on flooding, areas of inundation during and after rain, and weather forecasts,‚Äù the official said. Officials said the data is processed at the Decision Support Centre (DSC) at the National Remote Sensing Centre (NRSC) in Hyderabad and is disseminated periodically to the Centre and the state under the disaster management support programme of Isro. INSAT-3DR, an advanced meteorological satellite configured with an imaging system and an atmospheric sounder, provides data on various parameters like temperature and humidity to forecast weather.

#NovaSAR is an S-Band Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) satellite intended for #forest mapping, land use and ice cover monitoring, flood and disaster monitoring. I remember my first time I felt like I had found queer community: it was the summer before my senior year of high school, and I went to New York to study art at Parsons. The Sunday that I arrived in NYC, June 29 2003, was coincidentally the same day as New York City pride. The first person I met, Joe, and I decided to walk over to 5th Avenue and watch as the parade came down the street. More than anything, that summer served as an intensive in giving me understanding, language, and a sense of belonging in my own identity. I learned about and fell in love with the work of Catherine Opie, I spent afternoons at the piers with friends, I went to see Rent on Broadway with my friend Ojay, and knew that I was just beginning to figure out how expansive queer culture, and love, and relationships, and community can all be. I was enormously privileged to have that experience at 17 years old, and I know first hand how powerful and transformative it can be to have a supportive network of peers and mentors as we navigate our individual identities. In the spirit of that discovery, I'm proud to work with @fossil in support of #HMIxFossil #MakeTimeForGood. This pride month, Fossil is supporting the Hetrick Martin Institute with 100% of proceeds on the sale of their Live in Color watch going to HMI - the largest organization supporting LGBTQ youth and their families. As we celebrate 50 years since Stonewall, and 40 years since HMI opened it's doors, I want to aim the spotlight on the important organizations doing this work not just during Pride month, but all year long ???
